<body>
	<%@ include file="session.jsp"%>
	<%@ include file="top.jsp"%>
	<div class="row">
		<%@ include file="side.jsp"%>
		<div style="padding: 20px 30px 20px 10px;" class="col-md-10">
			<div style="font-size: 25px; font-weight: bold; color: #337AB7;">Interview
				Tips</div>
			<div style="width: 220px; height: 3px; background-color: #337AB7;"></div>
			<div style="padding-top: 20px;">
				In the current job market, you'd better have your act together, or
				you won't stand a chance against the competition. Check yourself on
				these 10 basic points before you go on that all-important interview.
				<div style="padding-top: 20px;"></div>
				<table cellspacing="0" width="100%">
					<tr>
						<td><img src="img/tip01.jpg" align="left" width="300px"
							height="200px"
							style="border: 1px solid #DDD; border-radius: 15px;">
							<div
								style="padding: 40px 40px 40px 340px; vertical-align: middle;">
								<div style="font-size: 20px; font-weight: bold;">1. Do
									Your Research</div>
								<div style="font-size: 16px; padding-top: 20px;">Researching
									the company before the interview and learning as much as
									possible about its services, products, customers and
									competition will give you an edge in understanding and
									addressing the company's needs. The more you know about the
									company and what it stands for, the better chance you have of
									selling yourself in the interview. You also should find out
									about the company's culture to gain insight into your potential
									happiness on the job.</div>
							</div></td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td><img src="img/tip02.jpg" align="right" width="300px"
							height="200px"
							style="border: 1px solid #DDD; border-radius: 15px;">
							<div
								style="padding: 40px 340px 40px 40px; vertical-align: middle;">
								<div style="font-size: 20px; font-weight: bold;">2. Look
									Sharp</div>
								<div style="font-size: 16px; padding-top: 20px;">Select
									what to wear to the interview. Depending on the industry and
									position, get out your best interview clothes and check them
									over for spots and wrinkles. Even if the company has a casual
									environment, you don't want to look like you slept in your
									outfit. Above all, dress for confidence. If you feel good,
									others will respond to you accordingly.</div>
							</div></td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td><img src="img/tip03.jpg" align="left" width="300px"
							height="200px"
							style="border: 1px solid #DDD; border-radius: 15px;">
							<div
								style="padding: 40px 40px 40px 340px; vertical-align: middle;">
								<div style="font-size: 20px; font-weight: bold;">3. Be
									Prepared</div>
								<div style="font-size: 16px; padding-top: 20px;">Bring
									along a folder containing extra copies of your resume, a copy
									of your references and paper to take notes. You should also
									have questions prepared to ask at the end of the interview. For
									extra assurance, print a copy of Monster's handy interview
									take-along checklist.</div>
							</div></td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td><img src="img/tip04.jpg" align="right" width="300px"
							height="200px"
							style="border: 1px solid #DDD; border-radius: 15px;">
							<div
								style="padding: 40px 340px 40px 40px; vertical-align: middle;">
								<div style="font-size: 20px; font-weight: bold;">4. Be on
									Time</div>
								<div style="font-size: 16px; padding-top: 20px;">Never
									arrive late to an interview. Allow extra time to arrive early
									in the vicinity, allowing for factors like getting lost. Enter
									the building 10 to 15 minutes before the interview.</div>
							</div></td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td><img src="img/tip05.jpg" align="left" width="300px"
							height="200px"
							style="border: 1px solid #DDD; border-radius: 15px;">
							<div
								style="padding: 40px 40px 40px 340px; vertical-align: middle;">
								<div style="font-size: 20px; font-weight: bold;">5. Show
									Enthusiasm</div>
								<div style="font-size: 16px; padding-top: 20px;">A firm
									handshake and plenty of eye contact demonstrate confidence.
									Speak distinctly in a confident voice, even though you may feel
									shaky.</div>
							</div></td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td><img src="img/tip06.jpg" align="right" width="300px"
							height="200px"
							style="border: 1px solid #DDD; border-radius: 15px;">
							<div
								style="padding: 40px 340px 40px 40px; vertical-align: middle;">
								<div style="font-size: 20px; font-weight: bold;">6. Listen</div>
								<div style="font-size: 16px; padding-top: 20px;">One of
									the most neglected interview skills is listening. Make sure you
									are not only listening, but also reading between the lines.
									Sometimes what is not said is just as important as what is
									said.</div>
							</div></td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td><img src="img/tip07.jpg" align="left" width="300px"
							height="200px"
							style="border: 1px solid #DDD; border-radius: 15px;">
							<div
								style="padding: 40px 40px 40px 340px; vertical-align: middle;">
								<div style="font-size: 20px; font-weight: bold;">7. Answer
									the Question Asked</div>
								<div style="font-size: 16px; padding-top: 20px;">Candidates
									often don't think about whether they are actually answering the
									questions their interviewers ask. Make sure you understand what
									is being asked, and get further clarification if you are
									unsure.</div>
							</div></td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td><img src="img/tip08.jpg" align="right" width="300px"
							height="200px"
							style="border: 1px solid #DDD; border-radius: 15px;">
							<div
								style="padding: 40px 340px 40px 40px; vertical-align: middle;">
								<div style="font-size: 20px; font-weight: bold;">8. Give
									Specific Examples</div>
								<div style="font-size: 16px; padding-top: 20px;">One
									specific example of your background is worth 50 vague stories.
									Prepare your stories before the interview. Give examples that
									highlight your successes and uniqueness. Your past behavior can
									indicate your future performance.</div>
							</div></td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td><img src="img/tip09.jpg" align="left" width="300px"
							height="200px"
							style="border: 1px solid #DDD; border-radius: 15px;">
							<div
								style="padding: 40px 40px 40px 340px; vertical-align: middle;">
								<div style="font-size: 20px; font-weight: bold;">9. Ask
									Questions</div>
								<div style="font-size: 16px; padding-top: 20px;">Many
									interviewees don't ask questions and miss the opportunity to
									find out valuable information. The questions you ask indicate
									your interest in the company or job.</div>
							</div></td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td><img src="img/tip10.jpg" align="right" width="300px"
							height="200px"
							style="border: 1px solid #DDD; border-radius: 15px;">
							<div
								style="padding: 40px 340px 40px 40px; vertical-align: middle;">
								<div style="font-size: 20px; font-weight: bold;">10.
									Follow Up</div>
								<div style="font-size: 16px; padding-top: 20px;">
									Whether it's through email or regular mail, the interview
									follow-up is one more chance to remind the interviewer of all
									the valuable traits you bring to the job and company. Don't
									miss this last chance to market yourself.<br />It is important
									to appear confident and cool for the interview. One way to do
									that is to be prepared to the best of your ability. There is no
									way to predict what an interview holds, but by following these
									important rules you will feel less anxious and will be ready to
									positively present yourself.
								</div>
							</div></td>
					</tr>
					</tbody>
				</table>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>
